#. <br>
msgctxt "mn56:29.56"
msgid "Bhagavato tassa sāvakohamasmi."
msgstr ""

#. </p><p>
#. <a class="sc" id="sc89"></a>
msgctxt "mn56:29.57"
msgid "Taṇhacchidassa buddhassa,"
msgstr ""

#. <br>
msgctxt "mn56:29.58"
msgid "Vītadhūmassa anupalittassa;"
msgstr ""

# The Chinese here evidently reads akkha, but especially in the context of ahuneyya I think yakkha fits better, as offerings to yakkhas are a major theme.
#. <br>
msgctxt "mn56:29.59"
msgid "Āhuneyyassa yakkhassa,"
msgstr ""

#. <br>
msgctxt "mn56:29.60"
msgid "Uttamapuggalassa atulassa;"
msgstr ""

#. <br>
msgctxt "mn56:29.61"
msgid "Mahato yasaggapattassa,"
msgstr ""

#. <br>
msgctxt "mn56:29.62"
msgid "Bhagavato tassa sāvakohamasmī”ti."
msgstr ""

# The whole passage pivots on the ambiguity between vanna as “colour, beautiful feature” (cf. anekavanna= many colors in Kd 1), which clearly underlies the simile (cf. also the similes of flowers held together by thread at Pj 1), and vanna as “praise”. The Kadā saṃyūḷhā pana te idiom is used at DN 21 of gatha. I try to bring out these connections.
#. </p></blockquote><p>
#. <a class="nya" id="nya30"></a>
#. <a class="pts-vp-pli" id="pts-vp-pli1.387"></a>
#. <a class="sc" id="sc90"></a>
msgctxt "mn56:30.1"
msgid "“Kadā saññūḷhā pana te, gahapati, ime samaṇassa gotamassa vaṇṇā”ti?"
msgstr ""

msgctxt "mn56:30.2"
msgid ""
"“Seyyathāpi, bhante, nānāpupphānaṃ mahāpuppharāsi, tamenaṃ dakkho mālākāro "
"vā mālākārantevāsī vā vicittaṃ mālaṃ gantheyya;"
msgstr ""

msgctxt "mn56:30.3"
msgid "evameva kho, bhante, so bhagavā anekavaṇṇo anekasatavaṇṇo."
msgstr ""

msgctxt "mn56:30.4"
msgid "Ko hi, bhante, vaṇṇārahassa vaṇṇaṃ na karissatī”ti?"
msgstr ""

#. <a class="nya" id="nya31"></a>
#. VAR: uggacchīti → uggañchi (bj) | uggañchīti (s1-3, pts1)
msgctxt "mn56:31.1"
msgid ""
"Atha kho nigaṇṭhassa nāṭaputtassa bhagavato sakkāraṃ asahamānassa tattheva "
"uṇhaṃ lohitaṃ mukhato uggacchīti."
msgstr ""

#. </p><p class="endsection">
msgctxt "mn56:31.2"
msgid "Upālisuttaṃ niṭṭhitaṃ chaṭṭhaṃ."
msgstr ""
